[2] Michigan: horse, human
Date: Sat 21 Sep 2019
Source: The County Press [edited]
https://thecountypress.mihomepaper.com/articles/mosquito-borne-virus-spurs-caution/


Three people have died in Michigan from Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE), and at least 4 others have been sickened. In Lapeer County, a horse has died from the mosquito-borne disease while an infected deer in Genesee County was euthanized. As a result, local and state officials have sounded the alarm.

The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) issued a warning Tuesday [17 Sep 2019] that urged people to cancel outdoor events scheduled around dusk, especially if those activities include children until after the 1st hard frost.

The DHHS announcement prompted Dryden Community Schools to spray its elementary school playground with insecticide Friday [20 Sep 2019] and warned parents not to let their children play there until Monday [23 Sep 2019].

North Branch Area Schools Superintendent Jim Fish canceled evening activities Thursday [19 Sep 2019] at the district's campus so APM Mosquito Control can spray mosquito control in the areas surrounding the playground, practice fields and other outdoor spaces around the district's 3 schools. He also announced the [27 Sep 2019] North Branch Elementary Family Fun Night and [30 Sep 2019] All-Star Reading Night have been moved inside the elementary school to be on the safe side.

EEE is a virus that causes inflammation in the brain (encephalitis) that can cause permanent neurological damage and death.

Health officials say the virus was discovered in Lapeer County after a horse died suspiciously. Its owner took the animal to Michigan State University for testing. Local horse owners are saying the horse died in the Lum area, but the owner doesn't want to be identified. They are urging other horse owners to have their animals vaccinated.

In addition to the human cases, as of [16 Sep 2019], 9 cases of EEE in horses had been confirmed in Barry, Kalamazoo and St. Joseph counties. None of the horses were vaccinated against EEE, and all the animals have died. Also, 5 deer in Barry, Cass, Genesee, Kalamazoo, and Van Buren counties have been confirmed with EEE infection and were euthanized due to the severity of their disease signs.

Bob Wheaton, a Health and Human Services spokesman, said this is the most serious EEE outbreak since 2001, when 6 people were sickened. Wheaton said EEE is the most deadly of all mosquito-borne diseases in Michigan, with a 33% mortality rate.

A Kalamazoo man who came down with the illness last month [August 2019] in Kalamazoo died in just 9 days. Although there is a vaccine for horses, there is no known vaccine for humans.

Michigan's high case count is not an outlier: 2019 appears to be the worst year for EEE cases in more than a decade across the nation. On average, 7 cases a year are reported to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), but this year [2019], at least 20 people have been diagnosed with EEE in Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Jersey and Rhode Island, as well as Michigan.

Only 2% to 6% of people who are bitten by mosquitoes carrying the virus go on to develop EEE. But in those that do, the illness hits hard and fast. Symptoms such as headache, high fever, chills and vomiting start 4 to 10 days after a person is bitten. As the disease progresses, the patient can experience disorientation, seizures and coma.

That, said Kathy Haskins, director of the Lapeer County Health Department, is because "Humans and horses are considered 'dead-end hosts', because the concentration of virus in their bloodstreams is usually insufficient to infect mosquitoes."

Birds and mosquitoes are the virus carriers, said Wheaton. He said getting EEE is difficult because 1st a black tail mosquito has to infect a bird, and then another species of mosquito, a cattail mosquito, has to bite an infected bird and then a human or other vulnerable species.

While only 2 of Michigan's 60 species of mosquitoes can carry the deadly virus, it's nearly impossible for most people to tell them apart, so Wheaton said the best thing to do is avoid mosquitoes. Wheaton urged people who must go out in the evening to use mosquito repellents containing DEET.

APM Mosquito Control, the Armada-based firm that supplies mosquito control services for Rich Township, North Branch and other mid-Michigan communities has stepped up its efforts. A spokesperson said the company has initiated additional surveillance activity in the immediate area of the infected deer detection. They added should additional mosquitoes test positive for EEE or mosquito populations increase, localized spraying will continue as weather conditions allow.

The CDC says the best way to avoid EEE is to avoid mosquito bites. That means using an EPA-approved mosquito repellent, wearing long sleeves and pants in wooded, swampy areas, and getting rid of standing water in flower pots, bird baths and anything else in your yard that holds water.

[Byline: Phil Foley]

