[The presence of Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) in the Northern and Midwestern states of the USA indicates the virus can appear anywhere mosquitoes are.

The prudent equine owner, trainer, stable manager, etc. will insist all horses are vaccinated, regardless of location. The recent articles in Ohio and Michigan indicate the disease is no respecter of location.

Please vaccine your horses. The vaccine is a series of at least 2 injections with approximately 3 weeks between injections. The EEE vaccine is often combined with Western equine encephalitis (WEE) and West Nile virus (WNV) and usually tetanus. EEE immunity wanes a bit rapidly, so in the case of an outbreak, owners should be aware to vaccine every 3-4 months.

Humans should be aware of mosquito breeding locations, which is any standing water. Water in a potted plant catch basin, or old tire, or other depressions capable of holding water, can breed mosquitoes. Clean up the standing water to decrease the breeding of mosquitos.

EEE can affect humans in the same fashion as horses: through a mosquito bite. Consequently, eliminating standing water prevents mosquitoes and thereby helps both horses and humans.

There are mosquito repellants for horses. Be sure to use one approved for use on horses.

In humans, the most effective way to prevent infection from EEE virus is to prevent mosquito bites. Mosquitoes bite during the day and night. Use insect repellent, wear long-sleeved shirts and pants, treat clothing and gear, and take steps to control mosquitoes indoors and outdoors.

Use Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)-registered insect repellents with one of the active ingredients below. When used as directed, EPA-registered insect repellents are proven safe and effective, even for pregnant and breastfeeding women.

- DEET
- Picaridin (known as KBR 3023 and icaridin outside the US)
- IR3535
- Oil of lemon eucalyptus (OLE)
- Para-menthane-diol (PMD)
- 2-undecanone

Find the right insect repellent for you by using EPA's search tool: https://www.epa.gov/insect-repellents/find-repellent-right-you.

Just as in horses, EEE can be fatal in people as well. Prevention of this disease is critical for your horse to survive and for you to avoid the disease. - Mod.TG

